11. Interview Explanation (30–60 sec)

> "First, I compute the distance from every cell to its nearest thief using Multi-Source BFS by pushing all thief cells into the queue at once. This gives each cell a safety value. Then the problem becomes finding a path that maximizes the minimum safety along the path. One solution is Binary Search on the answer and use BFS to check if a path exists using only cells whose safety is at least the candidate value. An even cleaner solution uses a Max Heap, similar to Dijkstra, where each state stores the minimum safety seen so far and always expands the currently safest path first."




---

12. Key Takeaways

Multi-Source BFS computes nearest distances efficiently.

Binary Search is applicable because the feasibility is monotonic.

The problem is a Maximum Bottleneck Path problem.

A Max Heap (Dijkstra variant) solves it in a single traversal after BFS.

Overall complexity is efficient enough for n = 400.



---

13. Common Mistakes

Running BFS separately from every thief (O(T × n²)), which is unnecessary.

Forgetting to initialize all thieves in the BFS queue.

Not checking if the start cell satisfies the current safeness threshold in the binary search solution.

Marking cells as visited too late, causing duplicate queue entries.

Using a min-heap instead of a max-heap in the optimal solution.

Updating the path safety with max() instead of min().

Using Euclidean distance instead of Manhattan distance.



